column13: An enclosed water heater boiler (1) for burning solid fuel is disclosed. The burner assembly (10) has two burners namely a granular fuel burner (11) and a fuel fired burner (12). The granular fuel burner (11) has a brazier fed with the granular fuel and the fluid fired burner (12) being mounted remote from the brazier such that the flame generated by the fluid fired burner (12) is directed beside and substantially away from the brazier. A flame transfer device (15) is provided to direct some of the flame generated by the fluid fired burner (12) as a concentrated jet against portion of the granulated fuel (25) to ignite the granular fuel allowing for extremely efficient ignition and a substantial reduction in CO generation. This burner assembly provides additional heat from boilers as required over short periods of time. <Figure 2>

column12: Improvements in or relating to remote handling tongs
column13: 925,596. Handling radio-active material. UNITED KINGDOM ATOMIC ENERGY AUTHORITY. June 23, 1961 [June 23, 1960], No. 22111/60. Class 39 (4). [Also in Group XXIII] Tongs for handling a radiation source tube comprises a fixed hand grip portion 1 connected to a hollow shaft 4 through which extends a rod 3 connected to a hand grip portion 2 pivoted on grip portion 1 whereby the rod may be axially moved. The shaft 4 is attached to a sleeve 5 receiving a sliding member 6, bellcrank levers 7, 8 being pivotally connected at 15, 16 to the member 6 and at 17 to an adaptor 19 at the end of the rod 3. A spring 24 acting between a cap 25 of the sleeve 5 and a block 26 abutting the adaptor 19 urges the parts towards the end 12 of the sleeve 5. The member 6 is guided for limited sliding movement by screws 20, 21 extending through slots 22, 23 in the sleeve 5. In operation the levers 7, 8 are passed over the flanged end cap of the source tube (Fig. 6, not shown), slots 28, 29 in the sleeve 5 permitting this action, the hand grips 1, 2 then being squeezed together so that the levers engage the cap, further squeezing of the grips causing the member 6 to be retracted against the action of the spring 24 so that the end of the source tube abuts the sleeve end 12. A steadying handle may be attached to the shaft 4 (Fig. 2, not shown). Specification 917,878 is is referred to.

column12: MULTIPLE-USE VERMIN TRAP APPARATUS, METHOD AND SYSTEM
column13: A vermin trap including a rotatable passage, the passage comprising an electrocution section and an open section, and a sensor for detecting vermin presence in the passage. When a vermin detection signal is sent to a controller, the controller causes electrification of the electrocution section and electrocution of the vermin, and the controller subsequently rotates the passage such that the vermin carcass is dumped downwardly through the open section. A method of using the vermin trap is disclosed, as is a system for indicating trap status and transmitting status indicators.

column12: Close-fitting garment and method for avoiding shingles scratching
column13: The garment made of stretchable material is adapted for an upper part of a body. The garment has front and back sections and a hem; a front of the hem is provided with a pair of slits, while a back—with a pair of apertures. A lace for fastening the garment to the upper part of the body is used. This lace has a pair of ends and is adapted to encircle a waist and to interact with the pair of slits and apertures. The first and second ends, after exiting from the pair of slits, are manipulated so as to extend downwardly and brought under the crotch area and then up toward the back of the wearer. There, first and second ends are inserted into the pair of apertures, behind lace, then brought forward, stretched and tied together.

column12: Coveyor systems for package irradiation plants

column13: A vibration sensitive switch has a pair of spaced apart parallel contacts (4) housed in a switch body (1,2,3) and a movably supported activated mass (5) inside a chamber (6) in the body. The mass (5) is supported by contact bridging means in the form of a pair of bars (14, 16) secured in the mass and located between the two contacts (4) with the centre of gravity (Cg) of the mass (5) spaced from the points of contact between the contacts (4) and the bars so that bars are urged against the contacts (4) by a lever action as a result of the gravitational force acting on the mass (5) . The forces at the contact points are thus greater than that which would be obtained by simply allowing the mass to rest on the contacts, which enables a relatively small mass to be used having a greater sensitivity to high frequency vibrations.

A snow removal device and method includes a core having provision for adhering snow to the core. This includes recesses which receive packed snow. Snow to be removed contacts the packed snow and adheres to the core. The core is rolled on a portion of a surface covered with snow so the snow from the surface communicates with the packed snow, clings thereto and builds upon the surface of the member as the member is rolled.

Improvements in or relating to conveyor systems for package irradiation plants
column13: 996,775. Traversers for elevated railways. UNITED KINGDOM ATOMIC ENERGY AUTHORITY. Oct. 29, 1963 [Nov. 12, 1962], No. 42631/62. Heading B7L. A conveyer system has carriers 4 with loads 3 continuously propelled along parallel tracks 1, 2 by a chain 6 having arms 5 engaging shanks 7 of the carriers; a traverser for moving carriers from track 2 to track 1 has a rail 10 mounted on a carriage 11 movable along a beam 12. An arm 16 engages a shank 7 to move a carrier on to rail 10 and then moves the rail 10 along beam 12 and finally moves the carrier on to track 1 where it is engaged by an arm 5; a further rotating arm 13 engages a shank 15 between rail 10 and carriage 11 to return the rail 10 to adjacent track 1. The spindles 14, 17, 8 of arms 13, 16 and chain drive wheel 9 are interconnected by chains 18, 21 the spindles 14, 17 being rotated at the same speed and at twice the speed of spindle 8. The spindle 14 of arm 13 is nearer track 1 than track 2 so that arms 13 moves out of engagement with shank 15 when carriage 11 is adjacent track 2. The carrier 4 is transferred from track 2 to track 1 and the carriage 11 returned to track 2 in the time taken for a carrier to advance through a carrier spacing distance along the tracks.

column12: Addressable content distribution systems and methods
column13: Systems and methods for providing and receiving addressable content may include an electronic device for receiving the content. The electronic device may receive a first data stream including targeting data criteria for a plurality of assets at the electronic device. The electronic device may determine a subset of the plurality of assets for storage on the electronic device. The electronic device may also receive a second data stream including the plurality of assets. The electronic device may identify each asset of the subset of the plurality of assets within the second data stream, and may store each asset of the subset of the plurality of assets at the electronic device.

column13: A slide locking motorcycle kick arm with a foot pedal and a kick arm shaft that is attachable to an engine kick starter, where the foot pedal can rotate to be in the kick start position and rotated out of the way when kick starting is completed. The foot pedal can be locked in either position, only when the foot pedal slides to the end of the kick arm shaft, and can be locked in the rotated position.

A slide locking kick arm includes a shaft connectable to an engine kick starter and a foot pedal which fits over the free end of the shaft for stowage and slides to the free end of the shaft where it can be pivoted outboard away from the engine to deploy. The shaft includes an offset as necessary to avoid interference by engine-mounted or vehicle mounted parts. A spring-loaded locking pin with one or more alignment plates may be incorporated to provide positive engagement.

column13: A security alarm system has a number of remote detectors coupled in a loop including a plurality of signal lines and a common return line. Each detector is arranged to provide current paths between a unique binary combination of the signal lines and the return line when activated to generate a corresponding condition of signals in an indicator unit coupled to the loop so as to provide an indication identifying the activated detector. The detectors may each incorporate a shock sensor connected in series in the return line for causing a momentary open circuit when activated, and a latching circuit coupled between selected signal lines and the return line. <IMAGE>

column12: Brake NOW! - a helmet mounted safety brake light
column13:
Simply stated, the Brake NOW helmet mounted brake light represents a breakthrough in rider safety by effectively alerting drivers behind them of their intentions to slow down or stop. The simple concept of putting a highly visible LED brake light directly on the rider's helmet has never been addressed before. 

   New laws have been passed requiring helmets to be worn while riding on public streets. Helmet manufacturers have gone to great lengths to make their product more impact resistant. They have also added unique paint and color schemes to make their helmets more visible. Nothing, however, comes close to the degree of safety that the Brake NOW warning light affords. 

    Working exactly on the same theory that now makes it mandatory for automobile manufacturers to have a higher mounted, 3 ^{rd} brake light in every car and truckthe Brake NOW helmet mounted brake light accomplishes the same recognizable effect. Being seen equates to being safer

column13: The subject dealt with herein concerns an intensifier tube which utilizes a channel-type electron multiplier. It is conventional to direct the output of such a multiplier onto an aluminized phosphor screen. However, poor resolution and aluminum layer damage results. column13: A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infra-red sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system.

column13: A method of transmitting both foreground data packets and background data packets as a signal stream on a link between a first network interface and a second network interface, said foreground data packets having a higher priority than said background data packets, which method comprises the steps of: (a) when foreground data packets are to be sent, allocating points in said signal stream, each of which will serve as a starting point for a foreground data packet, said points being defined by their position relative to framing symbols; and (b) said first network interface sending at least one foreground data packet with a header comprising an indication of the length of that foreground packet in said signal stream; and (c) all available space in said signal stream not occupied by foreground data packets or framing symbols being occupied by background data packets or, if there is no background data to be sent, idle data; whereby said points are able to be allocated in said signal stream for transmission of said foreground data packets without regard to the position of said background data packets in said signal stream, and said first network interface is able to transmit said background data packets without the overhead of adding fragment headers where they are interrupted by said foreground data packets.

column12: Electronic heater for high voltage applications
column13: A high voltage, high efficiency self-regulating heater comprises a thermally conductive housing having a chamber therein with a heating member in the chamber. The heating member includes a self-heating positive temperature coefficient (PTC) resistor element of a generally parallel-piped shape with its thickness dimension much less than its width dimension yielding two parallel face surfaces of larger area than two parallel edge surfaces. A layer of electrically conductive material is applied to the two parallel edge surfaces yielding an ohmic contact. The heater member further comprises two heat sink plates of thermally conductive, electrically insulating material which are positioned to engage the two broad face surfaces of the element. First and second terminal means are attached to the electrically conductive edge surfaces for supplying electrical power to the element to provide a heater in which the current flow is perpendicular to the major direction of heat flow to minimize banding of the element under high voltage use. The chamber is filled with an electrically insulating thermally conductive ceramic for providing good heat transfer.

ATHEROTHROMBOTIC DISORDERS: MUTATION IN THE FACTOR XIII GENE
column13: The invention relates to a mutation in the Factor XIII A-subunit gene. The Factor XIII A gene product catalyzes the covalent cross linkage of two glutamate amino acid residues with two lysine amino acid residues in the η-chain of fibrin followed by the polymerisation of α-fibrin to form a blood clot. This application describes how a point mutation in codon 34 of exon 2 which results in a Valine→Leucine substitution (Factor XIII Val34 Leu) is protective against atherothrombotic disorders and more specifically myocardial infarcation. This application describes a method and a kit for use in clinical diagnosis of thrombotic disorders and preventative prophylactics.

column12: Combination purse, key holder, and handguard
column13: A handguard comprises a key holder component and a purse component fastened to, and separable from, each other. Each component fits in a user's hand, and when used while carrying a plastic shopping bag, protects the hand from irritation etc. caused by heavily laden bags. Key holder component has a back piece and front piece stitched together to form a key compartment between them, the key compartment being open at its top edge, but closed by a flap on the back piece. Purse component has two members stitched together to form a purse compartment, which is open at the top and closed by fasteners inside the purse compartment. Each component has fasteners on their outer surfaces which fasten the key holder component to the purse component. The preferred fasteners are hook and loop fasteners. Key holder compartment has a key ring retained inside by a strap that slides through an opening at the key compartment bottom. A snap hook or D-ring is secured towards the other end of the strap by a fastener. A fastener on the strap joins another fastener on the key holder back piece outside, such that the handguard is strapped around a user's hand, or secures the two components together when the handguard is not being used as a handguard. The handguard can be used to carry keys, change, currency, credit cards, shopping list etc. so these items may be available for impromptu shopping after the user has engaged in activities such as jogging.

The technology provides embodiments for a waveguide including gaps which turn the direction of light. Each of a plurality of planes located within a waveguide includes a group of gaps so that each of the gapped planes partially reflects out of the waveguide light within a first angle range and transmits down the waveguide light received within a second angle range. In some examples, the waveguide is formed by joining optically transparent sections, and each group of gaps is formed in a surface of each optically transparent section which becomes a joining surface when bonded with an abutting all flat surface of an adjacent section. The waveguide may be used in displays, and in particular in near-eye displays (NED)s.

Printing-surfaces. - Printing-surfaces are made in pure Portland cement by casting on a flong, papier mÔchÚ, or other matrix in an apparatus such as is shown. If not properly type-high, the cast block may be made so by casting plaster of paris or the like on the back. As shown, a flong or matrix 1 preferably made impervious to moisture, by treating with oil or paraffin wax, is placed faceup on a glass or metal plate 2, to which it may be made to adhere by a coating of warmed paraffin wax. Plates 3 of glass or metal are placed round the matrix 1, and the Portland cement is run into the space 4, the apparatus being agitated to eliminate air bubbles. A glass plate 5 is placed on the top of the cement. When necessary, the block may be made type-high by casting on it a cement or plaster of paris backing, the block being placed face-down on a level surface on which are placed type-high supports for an oiled glass plate, which is applied to the back.

column12: SMOKING ARTICLE WITH DUAL FUNCTION CAP
column13: A smoking article (10, 100) is formed from two component parts. These parts are a rod (20, 120) comprising an aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) and a removable cap (30, 130). The removable cap (30, 130) can be coupled to the rod (20,120)in two configurations. In a first configuration, the removable cap (30, 130) is coupled to a first end (21, 121) of the rod (20,120) and a heat source (50, 150) located at or near a second end of the rod (20,120) heats the aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) to generate an inhalable aerosol. In a second configuration, the removable cap is coupled to the second end (22, 122) of the rod (20,120) and at least substantially covers the heat source (50, 150). The smoking article (10, 100) is arranged in the second configuration for disposal.

The present invention relates to a multicomponent aerosol-forming article defining a longitudinal axis, the article comprising: —a first rod-shaped component comprising a first longitudinal surface having a first and a second axially opposed ends, said first longitudinal surface being at least partially wrapped around the longitudinal axis in a first wrapping sheet; —a second rod-shaped component comprising a second longitudinal surface having a first and a second axially opposed ends, said second longitudinal surface being at least partially wrapped around the longitudinal axis in a second wrapping sheet, the first end of the second component being in direct abutment to the second end of the first component along said longitudinal axis; —wherein a portion of said second longitudinal surface at said first end of said second component is free of said second wrapping sheet; and—wherein said first wrapping sheet is wrapped for at least an overlapping length along the longitudinal axis on the second wrapping sheet.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR INTERMEDIATELY STORING DOUBLE-LENGTH SEMI-FINISHED PRODUCTS
column13: The method for intermediately storing double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products comprises the step of providing a tipping apparatus and forming double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products in the tipping apparatus. The method further comprises the steps of providing a cutting device and cutting the double-length semi-finished product into single products with the cutting device and providing a packer and packing single products in the packer. The method yet further comprises the steps of transporting the double-length semi-finished products from the tipping apparatus to the cutting device and transporting the single products from the cutting device to the packer, and intermediately buffering double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products in a buffer arranged between the tipping apparatus and the cutting device.

A multilevel container (200) for storing and presenting items (40) includes a supporting structure (220), first and second trays (20,2 10) mounted to the supporting structure for pivoting between a storage position wherein stored items are inaccessible to a user and an access position wherein the items are accessible, and a transmission mechanism coupling trays together, whereby as either tray is pivoted from the storage position to the access position, the other tray is pivoted automatically from the storage position to the access position, presenting the stored items to the user. Optionally, the container can include a reusable retail security device (80) receivable in apertures (71,61,211,18) preventing the trays from being pivoted and/or a child resistant catch (610) for a package containing pharmaceutical products. The container is simple, easy to use, offering an ergonomic design requiring little dexterity to operate which can be manufactured at high speed on existing equipment.

column13: A method of forming a semiconductor device comprises forming a control electrode over a portion of a semiconductor layer, forming recesses extending into the semiconductor layer on opposing sides of the control electrode, and forming doped regions in the semiconductor layer through the recesses. The doped regions form current electrode regions of the semiconductor device and each doped region extends into the semiconductor layer from at least a base of a recess. The method further comprises forming, after forming the doped regions, strained semiconductor regions in the recesses, wherein a junction between each doped region and the semiconductor layer is formed below an interface between a strained semiconductor region and the semiconductor layer.

Machine head for tuning a stringed instrument, especially a guitar or the like
column13: A machine head, especially for precision tuning of a guitar string or strings, avoids the slackness between the cog and worm gear drive of the existing design which can give rise to tuning slip and imprecise tuning. The proposed machine head has a spindle to which a string is secured at one end and carries an arm (2a). Adjusting screw (3) cooperates threadingly with an abutment (7) and the end of the adjusting screw bears on the arm whereby rotation of the adjusting screw determines the position of the arm and hence tension in the string.

column13: A high efficiency, self-regulating temperature-controlling fluid sump heater for external mount or internal well use comprising a D-shaped thermally conductive housing having a chamber therein and a plurality of heating elements in the chamber. The heating elements are self-heating, positive temperature coefficient (PTC) resistors having low initial resistance which increases abruptly as their temperature rises above a given level. The elements have first and second substantially parallel surfaces spaced one from another, these surfaces each having a layer of electrically conductive material applied thereto for forming on ohmic contact. The heater further comprises two heat sink plates of thermally and electrically conductive material, the plates being positioned to engage the first and second surfaces of the elements and to extend nearly the whole length of the housing with one plate adjacent the flat wall of the D-shaped housing. First and second terminal means are carried by the plates for supplying electrical power to the elements. The chamber is filled with an electrically insulating thermally conductive ceramic for providing better heat transfer while avoiding degradation of the PTC resistors.

An infra red intrusion detection system employs a transmitter unit having a plurality of transmitters (A t , B t , C t , D t ) arranged in a transmitter housing and a plurality of receivers (A r , B r , C r , D r ) arranged in a receiver housing that is separate from the transmitter housing. A transmitter controller (2, 4, 6, 8) causes the transmitters to transmits in a predetermined sequence and at a predetermined transmit rate. A receiver controller (20, 22, 24, 26) is arranged to read the receiver inputs in a predetermined sequence and at a predetermined receive rate. By arranging for the transmit and receive rates to be different, the need for a synchronising link between the transmitters and the receivers is avoided, thus providing simplification.

Telegraphs, mechanical.-In mechanical telegraphs for ships &c. in which the receiver and transmitter are connected by shafting, an intermediate actuating - mechanism is adapted to be thrown into and out of gear with the shafting, so that the apparatus can be actuated from two or more places. A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infra-red sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system. <IMAGE>

column13: An electrical connector is disclosed, designed for use with a telephone headset. The connector utilizes angled contacts for low insertion force, resulting in easier mating and longer life. The connector is provided with a latch that allows the connector to be uncoupled with a force roughly eight times the insertion force. Both halves of the connector have beveled edges on the upper surfaces only, allowing the connector to be aligned by tactile feel rather than visual inspection or by trial and error. Fine wires can be terminated on the connector contacts because the wires are accurately centered over insulation piercing points on the electrical contacts, and expansion of the wires in all directions is restricted as the piercing points penetrate the wire.

column12: Improvements in Typewriting Machines for Coding and Decoding Messages.
column13: 122,886. Grant, J. C. Feb. 4, 1918. Machines with two sets of types for coding and decoding. -A typewriter for printing code and original messages simultaneously is provided with two distinct sets of typewheels or shuttles which receive equal angular and equal axial movements at each key operation, one set being non- adjustable and the other set being adjustable in accordance with a code number. The adjustable type-wheels may be formed with a number of splines or castellations for engaging splines or castellations on the shaft. In the arrangement shown, anvils H, H<2> on a shaft C carry a set of four adjustable shuttles B<1> - - B<4> and a single non-adjustable shuttle A respectively. The shuttle A is provided with four rows of types arranged with like letters superposed. The shuttles B<1> - - B<4> have each one row of types with nine or more letters repeated at the ends to provide a sufficient range for the code. Before coding or decoding, the anvils are detached and the shuttles B<1> - - B<4> are set relatively forwards or backwards in accordance with the code number, and are then secured together and again coupled to the stop arm D of the action. Each of the shuttles is formed with a number of lettered or numbered holes b<2>, Fig. 3, for engaging a fork which secures the shuttles together. The stop arm D is formed with a finger d' which can engage one of a series of notches b<1> on each of the shuttles B<1> - - B<4> The finger d<1> engages also a single notch in the shuttle A. In a modification, the non-adjustable shuttle is mounted in a stationary anvil and bears only one row of type. The shaft C is moved axially at each key-operation in order to bring the shuttles B<1> - - B<4> successively into printing position. For this purpose, the shaft is supported by a cam W, Fig. 8, adapted to raise and then drop the shaft. The cam is provided with a ratchetwheel T engaging a detent Z and an operating pawl S on the shift-lever L<1>. The character-key levers may operate a universal bar on the lever L'. According to the Provisional Specification, the type-members may be successively moved into position by a spring or weight or by compressed air, a bell or buzzer being provided for indicating when the code figure has been completed; further, the type-wheels may be locked by a nut engaging a bayonet thread on the shaft. Sheet feeding and guiding arrangements; hammer-impression arrangements; ink-ribbon mechanism.-The coded and original messages are printed on the same sheet P, Fig. 1. which passes from rollers F', F<2> to feed-rollers F<3>, F<4> and is looped round a roller F<5>, arranged so that sufficient space is provided between the messages. The impression-hammer is formed with two striking-faces g<1>, g<2>. A horizontally arranged ink-ribbon may be provided for each set of type-wheels; or a single vertical ribbon may serve for both sets. Where a vertical ribbon is provided, the usual key for depressing the type-shuttles to render the writing visible may be arranged also to displace the ribbon laterally.

column12: Manufacture of Thread, Twine, or Cord from Paper or like Material.
column13: 136,614. Grant, J. C. Dec. 14,1918. Materials, special, for cords, &c. - Twine or cord is formed by twisting strips of paper obtained by joining, by an adhesive, sheets of paper of substantially rectangular form to form a strip of indefinite length, which may be divided into narrower strips and twisted, and, if necessary, the individual threads so formed are twisted together. The sheets may be joined by gumming a thin strip on either or both sides of the joint, or on the upper side of one sheet and on the lower side of the other; or by mean of a lap joint the edges of which are preferably of zig-zag or wavy contour. The agglutinant is of thin consistency and renders the contact surfaces pulpy so that the joint is consolidated under pressure. The strip may be waterproofed or treated in any well known manner before or after twisting. A suitable apparatus for jointing the sheets is shown in Fig. 1. Sheets are fed from two points so that those from one point are interposed in the space left between those from the other point. A roller 9 in continuous contact with a band 10 passing through a bath of adhesive 11, is oscillated so as to contact with the sheets, which pass between pressure rollers 5, 7 around heated rollers 12 and 15, and are wound on a spindle 16.

The technology provides embodiments for a waveguide including gaps which turn the direction of light. Each of a plurality of planes (202a, 202b) located within a waveguide (123) includes a group of gaps (250) so that each of the gapped planes partially reflects out of the waveguide light within a first angle range and transmits down the waveguide light received within a second angle range. In some examples, the waveguide is formed by joining optically transparent sections, and each group of gaps is formed in a surface of each optically transparent section which becomes a joining surface when bonded with an abutting all flat surface of an adjacent section. The waveguide may be used in displays, and in particular in near-eye displays (NED)s.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Casting Type.
column13: 20,398. Grant, J. C. Sept. 6. Trimming type ; moulds.-Type-casting moulds of the kind described in Specification 20,953/00, are constructed to produce " self-dressed " types v, such as are shown in Figs. 10, 11, and 12, the tangs o being so placed that, when broken off the types v, the rupture takes place towards one side of the type, and within the body of the type. The mould shown in Figs. 1, 2, and 5 for producing the type shown in Fig. 10 is formed from blocks a, b, c, d, spaced apart to receive an adjustable slide f, which determines the set width of the type, and is of the body shape and size of the type with its tang. The mould is closed by the matrix m and a slide l, a shielded plate e being provided to receive the nipple. When the cast has been made, the slide l is withdrawn, and the slide f is raised to carry the type and its tang to the top of the block c, the slide l is then advanced, and the tang o is broken off against a lug p. The slide f is reduced in thickness at the top, and plates q, r are secured to the reduced part so as to produce a slide of the shape of the mould cavity ; or the slide may be reduced on one side to receive a plate, and the other side of the mould may be stepped. The block c may be provided with ridges to produce nicks g in the type, the slide f being grooved to fit the ridges. The type shown in Fig. 11 is produced in a mould wherein the blocks b, d are replaced by a single block formed with a ridge which produces a groove y between the type and the tang, the slide f being formed with a groove which fits the ridge in the block. The type shown in Fig. 12 is produced by a mould such as that used for producing the type shown in Fig. 11, but not having the ridge in the single block. The blocks may be water-cooled.

column12: DEVICE FOR HOLDING A BOOK OPEN
INDIRECT DATA RETURN FROM MEMORY CONTROLLER LOGIC
column13: A portion of the memory space, supported by memory chips that are being controlled by a memory controller logic, can be set aside and read requests directed to memory addresses within that portion can be redirected, by the memory controller logic, to other memory addresses at which is stored the data equivalent to the internal data of the memory controller logic that the memory controller logic seeks to return, thereby enabling the memory controller logic to indirectly return data to processes executing on the host computing device. Additionally, requests to write data to specific memory addresses, including memory addresses that can be within the set aside portion, can be interpreted, by the memory controller logic, as commands that the memory controller logic is to perform, and which impact its own internal data including commands to reset values, or start or end data collection, or other like commands.

An infra red intrusion detection system employs a transmitter unit having a plurality of transmitters (A t , B t , C t , D t ) arranged in a transmitter housing and a plurality of receivers (A r , B r , C r , D r ) arranged in a receiver housing that is separate from the transmitter housing. A transmitter controller (2, 4, 6, 8) causes the transmitters to transmits in a predetermined sequence and at a predetermined transmit rate. A receiver controller (20, 22, 24, 26) is arranged to read the receiver inputs in a predetermined sequence and at a predetermined receive rate. By arranging for the transmit and receive rates to be different, the need for a synchronising link between the transmitters and the receivers is avoided, thus providing simplification.

column12: Method for determining the velocity of a three-dimensional fluid flow over a submerged body
column13: A method for determining the velocity of a three-dimensional fluid flow o a submerged body is provided. A plurality of finite volume cylindrical elements are used to represent the distribution of vorticity at the surface geometry of the body. The vorticity distribution is used to determine the velocity field of the flow according to the Biot-Savart integral which is solved for in a cylindrical coordinate system.

column13: A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infra-red sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system. <IMAGE>

column12: Transceiving a data stream comprising high and low priority data
column13: A method of transmitting both foreground data packets and background data packets as a signal stream on a link between a first network interface and a second network interface, said foreground data packets having a higher priority than said background data packets, which method comprises the steps of:(a) when foreground data packets are to be sent, assigning a point in said byte stream that will serve as a starting point for each foreground data packet; and(b) said first network interface sending each foreground data packet with a header comprising an indication of the length of that foreground packet in said signal stream;whereby said first network interface is able to use all available space in said signal stream not used by foreground data packets for transmission of background data packets. The foreground data packets may comprise time sensitive real-time data, such as audio, video or VoIP data, whereas the background data may comprise data that is not time sensitive. The method may further comprise transmitting background data packets in space in the signal stream that is allocated to but not used by foreground data packets. Step (b) may further comprise coding the length with a number of bits in the header, the number being variable such that a number of bits is used that is sufficient to indicate said length, whereby the length of the header is proportional to the length of its associated foreground data packet. The method may further employ separate foreground and background buffers.

A vibration sensitive switch has a pair of spaced apart parallel contacts (16) contained within a switch body (10) and a movably supported tubular mass (20) inside a chamber in the body. The mass (20) is supported with respect to the switch body (10) by conductive members in the form of two pairs of contact bars (22, 24, 26, 28) secured at each end of the tubular mass and located between the two contacts (16) so that both sets of bars are in electrical contact and resting on and between them by force of gravity. The contact bars (22, 24, 26, 28) are suitably arranged to cross each other at the axial centre of the tubular mass (20) and angled to provide a wedging action when at rest thus providing higher contact pressure than would normally be obtained. When a vibration occurs, the bridging connection between the contact bars (22, 24, 26, 28) and the contacts (16) is interrupted. <IMAGE>

A vibration sensitive switch has a pair of spaced apart parallel contacts (4) housed in a switch body (1,2,3) and a movably supported activated mass (5) inside a chamber (6) in the body. The mass (5) is supported by conductive members in the form of a pair of bars (14, 16) secured in the mass and located between the two contacts (4) with the center of gravity (Cg) of the mass (5) spaced from the points of contact between the contacts (4) and the bars so that bars are urged against the contacts (4) by a lever action as a result of the gravitational force acting on the mass (5). The forces at the contact points are thus greater than that which would be obtained by simply allowing the mass to rest on the contacts, which enables a relatively small mass to be used having a greater sensitivity to high frequency vibrations.

A vibration sensing device comprises an insulated housing having supported therein a weight and a centrally extending conducting shaft. Two spaced parallel conductors extend across the housing and engage the shaft, one above and one below the shaft and engaging the top of the shaft and the bottom of the shaft, respectively. The weight presses the shaft down on the nearer conductor and up against the farther conductor. The shaft thus acts as a lever using the near conductor as a fulcrum and pressing upwardly against the farther conductor. The shaft thus bridges the two conductors and connects them. The housing when mounted with the shaft horizontal maintains a closed circuit which will be opened when the housing is subjected to vibrations such as those occurring during a break-in. The opening of the circuit is used to actuate an alarm. The sensitivity of the device may be adjusted by moving the conductors with respect to one another, an adjusting screw available outside the housing being provided for this purpose.

column13: This is a new investment strategy which involves a new way to make a possibly decent return at a low risk. The new part of this process involves purchasing a long (or ultra long) fund of some index from a fund family. Also it involves simultaneously purchasing a short (or ultra short) fund based on the same underlying index from the same fund family. This strategy seeks to exploit the difference in percentage gained by the winner compared with a lesser percentage loss of the loser. This strategy also involves the already existing arts of technical and fundamental analysis in order to rebalance at a time when enough of a gain can be realized and when it becomes clear that the funds will change direction forcing the investor to buy low and sell high.

column13: The method and apparatus for manufacturing aerosol-generating semi-finished products comprise the steps of combining substantially cylindrical segments along a longitudinal first motion path. An infra-red intruder detection apparatus has an optical system comprising a Fresnel plate (7) and an infra-red sensor (5) positioned at the focus of the Fresnel plate. An optical path extending from the Fresnel plate to the infra-red sensor is bounded on either side by first and second mirrors (2, 3) diverging from the sensor towards the Fresnel plate to thereby provide a first fan of field of view for the sensor. A third mirror (4) is preferably disposed above the optical path to thereby provide a second fan of field of view for the sensor below the first said fan.

A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infra-red sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system. <IMAGE>

An electrical connector system includes two cooperating connector components, each of which includes a housing of electrically insulating material and a support body mounted for movement within the housing. Each support body carries a contact member and a magnet member, and biasing means retracts the support body into the housing. When the two connector components are in juxtaposed relation, magnetic forces produced by the aligned magnet members interact to draw the support bodies out of their housings and place the contact members in engagement to complete electrical circuits therebetween, the circuits being maintained by the magnetic forces and released when the support members are moved to an offset position. The magnets provide a constant closing force on the contact members when the magnets are aligned, irrespective of the positions or relative movement of the closure surfaces that they are monitoring. Thus, windows and doors that have loose fittings or may move while in the "secure" position are unlikely to cause intermittent circuit interruption of the monitoring connector system. When the window or door is opened, either by direct pull or by sliding action, the magnetic elements assist the support bodies to snap apart and the contact surfaces retract into their housings where they are less vulnerable to damage.

column13: Apparatus for the detection of infra-red radiation comprises a passive infra-red sensor (16), a focusing reflector (20) constructed and arranged to focus infra-red radiation received by the apparatus from a first range of distances from the apparatus, on the sensor (16) , and a focusing refractor (14) constructed and arranged to focus infra-red radiation received by the apparatus from a second range of distances from the apparatus, on the sensor (16), the second distance range encompassing distances shorter than the first distance range. The refractor may be a Fresnel lens (14) or an array of Fresnel lenses (32, 33, 34) formed in a polyethylene window (12) through which the radiation is transmitted. A wheel mounting clamp will hold a vehicle wheel securely on a wheel hub without the need for tightened wheel nuts or bolts. The clamp slides on to extended wheel studs and stops are attached to the ends of these studs. The central boss of the device is then turned using a detachable handle. This causes the front and rear parts of the device to move apart, lock up against the stops and the wheel, and consequently apply sufficient pressure to hold the wheel securely in place.

column12: SMOKING ARTICLE WITH DUAL FUNCTION CAP.
column13: A smoking article (10, 100) is formed from two component parts. These parts are a rod (20, 120) comprising an aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) and a removable cap (30, 130). The removable cap (30, 130) can be coupled to the rod (20,120)in two configurations. In a first configuration, the removable cap (30, 130) is coupled to a first end (21, 121) of the rod (20,120) and a heat source (50, 150) located at or near a second end of the rod (20,120) heats the aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) to generate an inhalable aerosol. In a second configuration, the removable cap is coupled to the second end (22, 122) of the rod (20,120) and at least substantially covers the heat source (50, 150). The smoking article (10, 100) is arranged in the second configuration for disposal.

column12: Method of forming a semiconductor device and semiconductor device
column13: A method of forming a semiconductor device comprises forming a control electrode (108) over a portion of a semiconductor layer (104), forming recesses (122) extending into the semiconductor layer (104) on opposing sides of the control electrode (108), and forming doped regions (150) in the semiconductor layer through the recesses (122). The doped regions (150) form current electrode regions of the semiconductor device and each doped region extends into the semiconductor layer (104) from at least a base of a recess (122). The method further comprises forming, after forming the doped regions, strained semiconductor regions (124) in the recesses (122), wherein a junction between each doped region (150) and the semiconductor layer (104) is formed below an interface between a strained semiconductor region (124) and the semiconductor layer (104).

column12: Indirect Data Return From Memory Controller Logic

column12: Apparatus and method for computing unsteady flows by direct solution of the vorticity equation
column13: Fluid flow characteristics are calculated directly from a two dimensional rface model of the object. A plurality of surface nodes with defined boundary conditions are established on the surface model. Consecutive layers of nodes are created a preset distance outward from said surface model. Curved panels are defined passing through three nodes at a layer, and a surface shape function is established for each panel from previous panels or from the boundary conditions. The fluid flow velocity for the next layer is developed from the velocities calculated at the previous layer and the shape function. Triangular elements are created by connecting a node on the next layer with two nodes from the previous layer to form an element. First and second vorticity gradients can be calculated for the current node at a time segment from the parameters associated with the previous layer of interest nodes at that time increment. This can be combined with the calculated diffusion velocity for the node to produce a rate of change of vorticity with respect to time which can be used to calculate the velocity of the fluid at the node.

The shaft a, Fig. 1, drives the speed and revolutiondirection indicator e by a bevel-wheel s, Fig. 2, and the counting-apparatus i through disconnectible helical gearing b, k. The wheel b is loose on the shaft a, to which it may be clutched by means of a lever g. The c o u n t e r may be arranged to register with the engines running in either direction, by connecting a crank driven by the gearing to a longer crank on the counter ; the long crank then only oscillates while the other rotates. A pointer q indicates the speed, and a co-axial pointer 10 revolves so as to indicate the direction of revolution of the shaft a. The mechanism for operating the pointer q consists of bevel-wheels s<1>, s<2>, Fig. 2, rotated in opposite directions by the wheel s, the wheel s<1> being fixed to its shaft t, and the wheel s<2> loose on this shaft. These wheels carry pawls to actuate ratchet - wheels u<1>, u<2>, which are arranged with their teeth in the same direction, so that one wheel is driven white the pawl moves idly over the other. The ratchet-wheels carry spur-wheels u<1x>, u<2x> gearing with wheels v on a shaft v<1>, and a wheel w on the shaft r<1> of a flyer-frame r gears with one of the wheels v. The flyer device is of a known type, consisting of a pivoted bracket r carrying a spindle with vanes driven through gearing from the. shaft r<1>, the rotation of the bracket, due to air resistance as the vanes rotate, being opposed by a spring or weight. The wheels v are mounted in a swinging frame suspended from the shaft r' of the flyer frame, so that they may be disengaged from the wheels u<1x>, u<2x> if required. The speed-indicating pointer q is carried on the shaft q<1> of the bracket r. The revolution-direction pointer 10 is rotated from the shaft t through spur gearing, and is carried on a sleeve 11 upon the shaft q<1>.

column12: Smoking article with dual function cap

A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infra-red sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system. <IMAGE>

A device for indicating the volume of liquid in a fuel tank or like container includes a linear variable differential transformer (LVDT) mounted within the tank, which is divided into a liquid containing section and a gas containing section by a longitudinally movable piston. Pressure gas is provided to the gas containing section of the tank through a port in a tank wall, and urges the piston to follow the liquid level in the tank. The LVDT has a fixed coil housing with a fixed electrical input and a rotatable core actuator. The core actuator is coupled for rotation in response to movement of the piston. Rotation of the actuator effects translational movement of the core within the coil, thereby producing a variable electrical output in response to changes in liquid volume.

column13: A method of forming a semiconductor device comprises forming a control electrode over a portion of a semiconductor layer, forming recesses extending into the semiconductor layer on opposing sides of the control electrode, and forming doped regions in the semiconductor layer through the recesses. A series of fast acting activated carbons is made having high surface areas and at the same time very small pore size. The method of manufacturing them, which specifies certain carbonaceous starting materials and pulverizing, agglomerating, crushing and oxidizing steps, determines or controls the pore sizes and surface areas. My activated carbon has highly uniform, very small pore sizes and at the same time a large surface area per unit of weight and a large macropore volume. New methods of separating mixtures of compounds, such as mixtures of hydrocarbons, are disclosed employing my new molecular sieve activated carbon. In my fast-adsorbing molecular sieve, molecules of generally lower molecular weight are adsorbed by the carbon rather than the usual case for activated carbon, which is that the carbon tends to adsorb generally larger molecules in preference to smaller ones.

Telegraphs, mechanical.-In a ship's telegraph in which the signals are transmitted by rotating a shaft through a certain number of turns in one direction or the :other, a shaft b, Fig. 1, driven by a shaft a can be disconnected from it at will by means of a clutch comprising a sleeve c, which engages the shaft a by an internal thread d and the shaft b by a longitudinal feather. For this purpose, an actuating-sleeve j is moved into the position shown in Fig. 1. The instrument connected to the shaft b may thus be put out of action ; but when the sleeve j is moved to the right, the two shafts automatically engage at the'moment when the instruments connected to them show the same indication. Two levers fare pivoted on the sleeve c at g and carry pivoted locking-pins n, which play through holes in the sleeve. When the clutch is in the disconnecting position, as shown, the levers f are held out against the spring m by toggle-links h pivoted on the actuating-sleeve j when the sleeve j is moved to the right, the springs m cause the pins to press against the shaft a, and as soon as the two shafts are brought to their correct relative position by turning the shaft a, they are locked by the pins n dropping into recesses p in the shaft a. To show when the shafts are in a locking position, or in which direction they differ from it, the end of the sleeve c carries a pointer and the shaft a is marked with a circumferential line and with arrow heads. The togglelinks h have projections which bear on the sleeve j to limit their motion, and one of them has a rounded catch which engages a spring bolt u so as to lock the sleeve j automatically when it is moved into the disconnecting position. According to the Provisional Specification, there may be a second catch to hold the sleeve in its other extreme position.

column13: The method and apparatus for manufacturing aerosol-generating semi-finished products comprise the steps of combining substantially cylindrical segments along a longitudinal first motion path. The following steps are performed along the first motion path: feeding a stream of at least three different segments along the first motion path, thereby arranging the at least three segments in alternating order, wrapping the stream of at least three segments in a sheet material to form an endless rod of segments, and cutting the endless rod of segments, thereby separating the endless rod of segments into wrapped segment rods. The method also comprises the step of processing wrapped segment rods along a second motion path, wherein the following step is performed along the second motion path: receiving the wrapped segment rods in flutes of a fluted receiving drum, wherein an end of the first motion path is aligned with a longitudinal axis of the flutes of the fluted receiving drum.

método e aparelho para a fabricação de produtos geradores de aerossol semifinalizados
column13: a presente invenção refere-se ao método e o aparelho para fabricação de produtos geradores de aerossol semifinalizados que compreendem as etapas de combinação dos segmentos substancialmente cilíndricos ao longo de uma primeira trajetória de movimento longitudinal. as seguintes etapas são realizadas ao longo da primeira trajetória de movimento: alimentar um fluxo de pelo menos três segmentos diferentes ao longo da primeira trajetória de movimento, dispondo, desse modo, os pelo menos três segmentos em ordem alternada, envolver o fluxo de pelo menos três segmentos em um material de folha para formar uma coluna contínua de segmentos, e cortar a coluna contínua de segmentos, separando, desse modo, a coluna contínua de segmentos em colunas de segmento envolvidas. o método compreende também a etapa de processamento das colunas de segmento envolvidas ao longo de uma segunda trajetória de movimento, em que a seguinte etapa é realizada ao longo da segunda trajetória de movimento: receber as colunas de segmento envolvidas em estrias de um tambor de recebimento estriado, em que uma extremidade da primeira trajetória de movimento está alinhada com um eixo longitudinal das estrias do tambor de recebimento estriado.

column13: A method for debiting tolls against vehicles travelling on multiple toll road networks (2-4), the tolls incurred in each toll road network being processing by a separate toll collection system (4-6), the method including the steps of: (a) creating a local user record identifying a user of a first of the toll road networks in a first local user identification register (19, 20) maintained by a first of the toll collections systems (14); (b) creating a global user record identifying the user in a global user identification register (30-31) maintained by a central tolling information exchange (28); (c) detecting the presence of a user identification device associated with the user on a second toll road network (3); (d) attempting to locate a second local user record identifying the user from a second local user identification register (21, 22) maintained by a second of the toll collection systems (5), and if unsuccessful; (e) attempting to locate the global user record identifying the user from the global user identification register (30, 31), and if successful; (f) deriving a toll charge incurred by the user on the second toll road network.

column13: A passive infra-red detection apparatus is described, which comprises an infrared sensor array (16) mounted in a housing (10), and a focusing reflector system (20, 22) and focusing refractor (14) which focus infra-red radiation from different distance ranges onto the sensor array (16). The sensor array (16) comprises at least three sensing elements or groups of elements (16A, 16B, 16C) spaced apart transversely with respect to the lens axis of the focusing refractor (14). Thus in combination with a multiple reflector (20, 22) having at least three reflector surfaces and/or a multiple focusing refractor (14), the sensor array receives several different views spaced apart transversely thereby providing a wider viewing angle than the prior art construction. Thus, the present detector is more suited to use with a closed-circuit television (CCTV) surveillance system.

column13: A smoking article (10, 100) is formed from two component parts. These parts are a rod (20, 120) comprising an aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) and a removable cap (30, 130). The removable cap (30, 130) can be coupled to the rod (20,120)in two configurations. In a first configuration, the removable cap (30, 130) is coupled to a first end (21, 121) of the rod (20,120) and a heat source (50, 150) located at or near a second end of the rod (20,120) heats the aerosol-forming substrate (55, 155) to generate an inhalable aerosol. In a second configuration, the removable cap is coupled to the second end (22, 122) of the rod (20,120) and at least substantially covers the heat source (50, 150). The smoking article (10, 100) is arranged in the second configuration for disposal.

A receptacle (18) for solid and/or liquid foodstuffs useful in boats is supported via interengagement between a first member (10, 110) attached to a substantial upright surface (14) and a second member (15, 215) attached to, integral with or adapted for cooperation with, the receptacle (18). The first member (10, 110) comprises a vertical elongate cavity (11, 111) having a vertical elongate opening (12, 112), and the second member (15, 215), for example an arm/handle of a vessel affording the receptacle (18) or a member which cooperates with the receptacle (18), comprises an end portion (16, 216) which may enter and move along the cavity (11, 111) but which is larger in cross-section than the opening (12, 112). <IMAGE>

column13: A vibration sensitive switch has a pair of spaced apart parallel contacts contained within a switch body and a movably supported tubular mass inside a chamber in the body. The mass is supported by conductive men, bets in the form of two pairs of contact bars secured at each end of the tubular mass and located between the two contacts so that both sets of bars are in electrical contact and resting on and between them by force of gravity. The contact bars are suitably arranged to cross each other at the axial center of the tubular mass and angled to provide a wedging action when at rest thus providing higher contact pressure than would normally be obtained.

column12: Method and apparatus for intermediately storing double-length semi-finished products
column13: The method for intermediately storing double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products comprises the step of providing a tipping apparatus and forming double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products in the tipping apparatus. The method further comprises the steps of providing a cutting device and cutting the double-length semi-finished product into single products with the cutting device and providing a packer and packing single products in the packer. The method yet further comprises the steps of transporting the double-length semi-finished products from the tipping apparatus to the cutting device and transporting the single products from the cutting device to the packer, and intermediately buffering double-length substantially cylindrical semi-finished products in a buffer arranged between the tipping apparatus and the cutting device.

column13: 2178. Warren, J. G. Jan. 27. Captive balls.-Apparatus for practising golf strokes, in which the distance to which the ball would have travelled had it been free is indicated upon a dial, and the failure to hit the ball true, that is without either 'pulling ' or 'slicing' it, is made known audibly. The ball b is mounted on a screwed spindle b<6>, so that it may be elevated any desired amount above the casing a, which is let into the ground, so as to be flush with the surface. The lower end of the spindle forms a sphere b<1>, turning in suitable bearings c. When struck, the ball passes below the edges of the casing, carrying the thin rubber membrane a<5> with it, and its spindle forces the cradle cross-piece e<3> round against the action of the springs e<5> to an extent proportionate to the strength of the blow. The cradle has a projection e<6> which strikes against a pointer f travelling over a graduated dial f<1>. Should the ball be not hit straight ahead, an arm b<8>, carrying a striker, moves to one side or the other and strikes one of two differently-sounding bells d. These bells are elliptical, so as to he adjustable at varying distances away from the central line between them. The ball is retained in its normal position by a spring b<9>.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Typecasting and Composing and like Machines.
column13: 7924. Grant, J. C. April 2. [Cognate Application, 25,031/09.] Single-type composing and casting machines; matrices.-Relates to machines for casting a line of individual type from aline of previously assembled matrices and consists in producing the type at one operation or pouring using character and space matrices having one or more integral mould walls. Fig. 1 shows a character matrix a employed in the machine in which the cavity is impressed upon a prominence 2, and a projection 3 equal in length to the height of the type to be produced is provided upon an attached separate thickness of metal and is employed to act as a wall of the mould cavity. The two parts of the matrix may be constructed of different materials. The shape of the matrix lugs prevents the prominence 2 from being damaged. Two-letter matrices of the type shown in Fig. 1 with a fount-discriminating notch for use with a double magazine, and multiple-letter matrices, all provided with the projections 3, are described, the prominences 2 being sometimes omitted. A single character may extend over adjacent matrices in the same or successive lines ; lines in bordered or tabular matter may similarly be produced. Assembly, justification, casting, and distribution are effected as described below. Assembling matrices.-The matrices are released from magazine channels for de'ivery into the assembly-box, by a key-operated power-relay escapement-mechanism as in the Mergenthaler machine. The escapement-dogs coact with the lugs 5 of the matrices. Fig. 2U shows the assembly box g in its normal positon with the matrices assembled on ledges 212, 221, 213 and with a matrix-arresting lug 210 and star-wheel z<1>. The ledge 221 is supported on pivoted arms 220, which may be thrown forward for providing access to the box. When a line of matrices has been assembled, the box is swung upon the shaft 211 through a right-angle. The matrices are then supported on ledges 213, 214, the ledge 214 being movable by means of a lever 215, and are swept onwards along raceways towards the casting position. Clamping and justifying matrices; spacers; justifying type.-Fig. 3 shows a wedge space-matrix b comprising two parts which are movable apart by a wedge 26, a prominence 22 on one part co-operating with a recess 23 in the other. According to the Provisional Specification, the wedges may move in the direction of the length of the cast type. Ordinary space or quad matrices, similar to the character matrices but with higher prominences 2, are also employed. Four separate methods of line-justification are described. According to the first three methods, as the width of the type is not dependent upon the thickness of the matrix, each matrix is made double or proportionately greater in set-width than it normally would be, and all the wedge space-matrices, unlike the character matrices, have a constant additional width. In the fourth method however, the additional width of character and wedge space-matrices alike is a single constant. This constant is the entire width of the projection 3, which is not the case in the other methods. Figs. 22 and 23 show the mechanism employed for the first method of justification. The wedge space-matrices are released from a magazine 104 by the operation of a key which simultaneously actuates an anchor escapement i and allows a screw j<1> to move a jaw 107 through a distance equal to the constant upon each wedge space-matrix. The parts are hereinafter described in connexion with matrices which are double their normal width, and so the jaw 107 is initially set for a line double the length of the line of type to be cast. When the assembled line nearly attains the proper measure, a special bell-ringing gear h is actuated, and on its completion, the operator moves a starting-handle which rotates the box g to its upper position, as shown in Fig. 22, and actuates the various parts of the machine. The matrices are swept from the box g along raceways 109 over a table k<1>, and the box returns to normal position for the composition of the next line. The motion of the gear j<1> in moving the jaw 107 from its zero position is communicated by a gear j<2> to a measuring vice-jaw 110, but, when the box g returns to normal position, the gear j<1> also returns the jaw 107 without returning the jaw 110. The line of matrices is held between the jaws 110, 111, which are movable transversely into the raceway, and the table k<1> is moved upwards to expand the wedge space-matrices by means of screw-mechanism 251, 253 as shown. A similar table x<1> for justifying the matrices at the mould is simultaneously moved upwards to half the extent of the table k<1>. The wedges of the space-matrices are next pushed down to their normal position by means of a pusher 112, the table k<1> having first been moved down, and the matrices are further swept along between the transversely-movable mould end jaws 115, 116. During this movement, the wedges are moved up by a lever to the level of the table x<1>, upon which they then come to rest. A screw 70, driven through an adjustable connexion 87, 88, is next rotated to close the jaw 116 upon the line of matrices, which are then held in position to cast a line of separate correctly justified type. The jaws 107, 110 can be set for various lengths of line. The jaw 110 returns to a position corresponding to that to which the jaw 107 has moved in the composition of the succeeding line. In the second method of justification, not only the measuring- jaw 110 but the left-hand mould jaw 116 are moved by gearing from the assembly-jaw 107. The right-hand jaws 111, 115 are movable towards the left by means of a wedge action produced by a rising table, the movement of the jaw 115 being half that of the jaw 111. The wedges of the space-matrices are not pushed up to justify the line when it has been moved from the assemblybox, but the line is clamped by the movement of the jaw 111. The line being afterwards conveyed between the mould-jaws 115, 116 which have been set as described, the wedges of the space-matrices are pushed up to produce the correct justification for the casting operation. In the third method of justification, mechanism for which is shown in Fig. 49, the assembly-jaw 160 is fed by a screw 164 and escapement i from its zero position at each release of a wedge space-matrix through a distance equal to the space-matrix constant, the mould-jaw 169 being geared to move through the same distance. When the line is complete, actuation of the starting-handle raises an abutment 162 into the delivery end of the box g, the abutment being either narrow or forked to coact with a double or narrow star-wheel z<2>, and the screws 164, 165 are locked against rotation by a stop 172 engaging a coupling 173, 174. Rotation of a shaft 178 next causes gearing to rotate pinions 58, 59, which operate nuts in the jaws 160, 169 so as to move these jaws, the jaw 169 moving half as far as the jaw 160. The jaw 160 clamps the line of matrices against the abutment 162, and, the assembly-box being then rotated, the coupling 173, 174 is released, the screw 164 moved back to its zero position for a fresh line, the abutment 162 returned, and the completed line swept in front of the mould. The jaws 160, 169 may be moved by means of wedges. The wedges of the spacematrices are then pushed up by the table x<3> to expand the line between the jaws 169, 170 ready for the casting operation. The screw 164 is returned to its zero position by means of gearing 187 from a sector 186 which records the addendum of the space constants. After the cast, the jaw 169 is slackened by means of gearing from a sector 189, and is then allowed to return to a position determined by the sector 186, which corresponds to an addendum of wedge space-matrix constants in the new line being composed. The jaws 160, 169 are now moved to the left through the distance which they were closed to the right during the justification of the preceding line. This brings the jaws themselves to what would be their zero position had they not been moved during the composition of the new line, and is accomplished by re-coupling the parts 173, 174 and rotating the shaft 178 back to its original position. Back-spacing gear zy for the jaws 169, 160, used for example when a wedge space-matrix is removed from the line, may also be employed in the first and second methods of justification. The escapement i is arranged so that it may be driven backwards. A pointer-and-scale device shows the length of the line in the assembly-box. In the fourth method of justification, each key depression, whether for character or space-matrix, causes a movement of the jaw in the assembly-box. When the line is complete it is moved opposite the mould, and the wedges of the space-matrices are elevated to clamp the line between the mould-jaws, the left-hand one of which has been moved simultaneously with the assembly-jaw by a ratchet escapement. In the meantime, the assembly-jaw has been returned to zero position for the new line, and, after the cast, the mould-jaw is returned by special means to a position determined by that of the assembly-jaw. In this method of justification, tLe movable mould-jaw is wide enough to cover that part of the tang orifice which in some cases may not be occupied by matrices. The escapement of the various justification mechanisms is driven through a friction clutch which may be disengaged to allow backward rotition of the escapement. Moulds.-Fig. 26 shows the upper and lower vertically movable mould blocks 113, 114 between which the projections on the matrices and the mould end vice-jaws extend to divide the mould into as many divisions as there are matrices. The foot of the type is formed by vertically movable tang-pieces 117, 118 against which bears the mouth of the metal pot. Trimming type.-After the cast, the metal pot is retired, the mould-block 113 is lifted, the mould end jaws are slackened

column13: 본 발명은 길이 방향 축을 한정하는 다중 구성 요소 에어로졸 형성 물품에 관한 것으로서, 이 물품은: - 제1 및 제2 축방향 대향 단부를 갖는 제1 길이 방향 표면을 포함하는 제1 로드 형상의 구성 요소로서, 상기 제1 길이 방향 표면은 제1 래핑 시트에서 길이 방향 축 둘레에 적어도 부분적으로 래핑되는, 제1 로드 형상의 구성 요소; - 제1 및 제2 축방향 대향 단부를 갖는 제2 길이 방향 표면을 포함하는 제2 로드 형상의 구성 요소로서, 상기 제2 길이 방향 표면은 제2 래핑 시트에서의 길이 방햐 축 둘레에서 적어도 부분적으로 래핑되고, 제2 구성 요소의 제1 단부는 상기 길이 방향 축을 따라 상기 제1 구성 요소의 제2 단부에 직접 접하는, 제2 로드 형상의 구성 요소를 포함하고, - 상기 제2 구성 요소의 상기 제1 단부에서의 상기 제2 길이 방향 표면의 부분은 상기 제2 래핑 시트를 갖지 않고, - 상기 제1 래핑 시트는 제2 래핑 시트 상에서 길이 방향 축을 따르는 적어도 중첩 길이에 대해 래핑된다.

column12: Belt drive system for a magnetic tape cassette transport/accessor
column13: Disclosed is magnetic tape cassette transport apparatus for use with a magnetic tape cassette storage and utilization system. Magnetic tape cassettes are transported between locations in the system by means of a cassette transport/accessor assembly, which is actuated by a belt drive system using stationary drive motors. This drive system eliminates the need to mount drive motors on the transport assembly, thus effecting a lighter weight, less complex assembly. The transport/accessor assembly includes two vertical rails rigidly mounted on upper and lower wheel carriages which travel on spaced horizontal rails adjacent to the cassette storage and utilization system. An accessor platform travels vertically on the vertical rails. The accessor platform supports a pair of cassette accessor assemblies which insert and extract a cassette from a location in the cassette storage and utilization system. The power for driving the cassette transporter/accessor assembly is provided by stationary motors coupled to the transport/accessor assembly through sprocket driven, high-yield stainless steel belts. Separate motor and belt drive systems provide selective movement of the transport/accessor assembly in horizontal, vertical and lateral directions.

column12: Smart card reader with electrostatic discharge protection
column13: Apparatus and methods for removing electrostatic charge from a generally non-conductive object that is inserted into a port or receptacle of a housing are disclosed, such as a smart card having an electrostatic charge thereon inserted into a slot of a housing of a smart card reader. Certain ones of the apparatus and methods use a housing including a slot for receiving a generally non-conductive object having an electrostatic charge thereon, and an electrically ungrounded array of protrusions disposed proximate the slot. Selected ones of the protrusions have a sharp tip. The electrostatic charge on the object and the sharp tips generate an electric field that is used to neutralize the electrostatic charge on the object so as to prevent damaging electric shock.
